<div class="explanation">
  <div class="exp-section bug">
    <h3>🐛 Why the Buggy Version Fails</h3>
    <p>Each task reads <code>sharedProgress</code>, adds its chunk, then writes back — a classic <strong>read-modify-write</strong> race:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Task A reads <code>progress = 40</code></li>
      <li>Task B reads <code>progress = 40</code> (same snapshot!)</li>
      <li>Task A writes <code>progress = 60</code> (+20)</li>
      <li>Task B writes <code>progress = 60</code> (+20 again, overwriting A's result)</li>
      <li>Net effect: only +20 instead of +40 → <strong>lost updates</strong></li>
      <li>Or tasks accumulate beyond 100 → <strong>overflow</strong></li>
      <li>JS is single-threaded but <code>await</code> yields control between tasks, creating the interleaving window</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="exp-section fix">
    <h3>✅ How the Fix Works</h3>
    <p>Updates are serialized through a <strong>Promise-based async queue (mutex)</strong>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Each task enqueues its update; the queue processes one at a time</li>
      <li>A <code>lock</code> Promise chains updates sequentially: <code>lock = lock.then(update)</code></li>
      <li>No two tasks can be inside the critical section simultaneously</li>
      <li>Progress increments are clamped to <code>[0, 100]</code> as an extra guard</li>
      <li>Result: monotonically increasing, no skips, no overflow, correct final value</li>
      <li>This pattern mirrors <code>Mutex</code> / <code>Semaphore</code> in multi-threaded languages</li>
